In article <2qnm7e$sb@scafell.gtl.demon.co.uk>,
Andrew Haisley <andrewh@gtl.demon.co.uk> wrote:
>
>Does anyone know of a secure encryption technique that allows
>ciphertext to be decrypted using one of two keys. It goes
>without saying that neither key should be easily derivable from
>the other.

You could encrypt your data with a "session key" then tag this session
key on to the front of the ciphertext twice. Encrypt the first session
key copy with key #1 and the second with key #2. Anyone in posssesion
of key #1 or key #2 can get at the session key and decrypt the
ciphertext.

Regards,

- Andy <asb@cs.nott.ac.uk>
